The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation
		 Thursday, June 17, 2004 				 Governors
																								New Delhi, June 16: The Manmohan Singh government today appointed two senior Congress leaders  former Lok Sabha Speaker Balram Jakhar and former junior foreign minister R.L. Bhatia  as governors of Madhya Pradesh and Kerala, giving a clear signal to the BJP appointees to gracefully step down, reports our special correspondent. 																								Prithviraj Chavan, the minister of state in the PMO, told reporters the Centre was merely filling in the two vacant positions and had not yet taken a decision to sack the BJP governors who have refused to vacate. 																								R.P. Gupta and Sikander Bakht, the governors of Madhya Pradesh and Kerala, had both died in harness.																								Chavan said the general rule was to step down, but refused to spell out if the Centre would sack the former governments appointees. 																								Rajasthans governor Madan Lal Khurana, Bihars Rama Jois, who is also a VHP member, Goas Kidar Nath Sahni, Haryanas Bhai Parmanand, Gujarats Kailashpati Triparthi, Uttar Pradeshs Vishnu Kant Shastri are some of the National Democratic Alliance nominees that the Centre wants to replace. 
